        "excerpt": "We will not conceal them from their children, but tell to the generation to come the praises of the LORD, and His strength and His wondrous works that He has done.",
        "body": "Asaph opens with a vocabulary of instruction: 'listen... incline your ears... my instruction (*torah*)... I will open my mouth in a parable (*mashal*)... dark sayings (*chidah*) of old' (vv.1-2). The pairing of *mashal* (parable) and *chidah* (riddle, dark saying) is significant — Matthew 13:35 quotes verse 2 as fulfilled in Jesus's parabolic teaching, identifying the psalm's riddle-structure as messianic in its depth. Asaph is not simply telling stories; he is unlocking a mystery embedded in Israel's history that requires interpretive eyes to see.\n\nThe covenant mandate in verses 5-7 is divine, not Asaph's own innovation: 'He established a testimony in Jacob and appointed a law in Israel, which He commanded our fathers that they should teach them to their children' (v.5). The Deuteronomic background is unmistakable — Deuteronomy 4:9, 6:7, and 11:19 all command precisely this intergenerational teaching. Asaph is not inventing a program; he is enforcing an already-standing divine command. The three-generation chain of transmission in verses 5-6 (fathers → children → children yet to be born) frames the entire psalm as a performance of that mandate: Asaph telling the story *is* the covenantal act.\n\nThe purpose of the transmission is explicitly theological, not merely educational: 'that they should put their confidence in God and not forget the works of God, but keep His commandments' (v.7). Trust, memory, and obedience are the three outcomes. The negative counterpart in verse 8 names the alternative: a generation that is stubborn (*sarar*), rebellious (*marah*), with unprepared heart and unfaithful spirit. The 'stubborn and rebellious' vocabulary is drawn directly from Deuteronomy's curse-section (Deuteronomy 21:18-21) — Asaph is telling his audience that the children who do not receive this transmission become covenant-breakers by default.\n\nFor the original post-Solomonic audience, this opening was an indictment. The northern kingdom had already demonstrated in living memory what a generation that did not transmit covenant faith looked like. Asaph's psalm was a warning that Judah was not immune to the same failure.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mashal* (parable, v.2) = a comparison, a proverb, a teaching-narrative with embedded meaning. *Chidah* (dark saying) = a riddle requiring interpretation — not obscure for the sake of obscurity but containing a depth that rewards sustained engagement. *Torah* (instruction, v.1) = not merely 'law' in a legal sense but teaching-instruction in the wisdom tradition."
