        "body": "The second historical loop opens with a diagnosis of Israel's fundamental problem: 'They did not remember (*zakhar*) His power, the day when He redeemed them from the adversary' (v.42). The word *zakhar* — to remember with the intention of acting on the memory — is the positive obligation Israel persistently violated. The Exodus was not obscure; it was the defining event of national existence. Every Passover, every sabbath, every festival reconfirmed it. And still they forgot.\n\nAsaph's plague catalog (vv.44-51) is selective and theological rather than exhaustive. He names blood (v.44), flies and frogs (v.45), locusts and grasshoppers (v.46), hail (vv.47-48), and the death of the firstborn (v.51) — omitting lice, boils, and darkness. The selection emphasizes plagues that comprehensively destroyed Egypt's agricultural, economic, and dynastic foundations. The climax is verse 49: God 'sent upon them His burning anger, fury and indignation and trouble, a band of destroying angels.' The four Hebrew synonyms for wrath (*charon*, *evrah*, *zaam*, *batstsarah*) pile up to communicate that God deployed the full weight of His judicial anger against Egypt — and that this is the God who was now being forgotten and tested by Israel in the wilderness.\n\nThe pivot at verse 52 is one of the psalm's most beautiful: 'But He led forth His own people like sheep and guided them in the wilderness like a flock.' The same God who commanded destroying angels against Egypt is the shepherd who leads the flock safely through the sea (v.53). The contrast is not arbitrary — it defines who God is to His covenant people versus what He is to His enemies. For Israel, every wilderness provision was the act of a shepherd. Their rebellion was refusing to be led; their sin was acting as if the shepherd were absent or insufficient.\n\nThe conquest summary (vv.54-55) is equally compressed but theologically rich. God brought them to 'His holy land' (v.54) — the land is defined by its possessor, not its geography. He drove out nations, apportioned the inheritance, and settled the tribes in their tents (v.55). The language is all divine passive — Israel did not conquer Canaan; God cleared it for His flock. This makes the apostasy of verse 56 all the more inexplicable: the very settlement that God accomplished became the platform from which Israel provoked Him.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Padah* (redeemed, v.42) = to ransom by payment — Exodus language for God's purchase of Israel out of Egyptian bondage. *Tson* (flock/sheep, v.52) = the standard word for a flock of small animals (sheep and goats) cared for by a shepherd — the pastoral metaphor that connects God's wilderness leadership to David's sheepfold origins in vv.70-72."
